it examines how these ordinary, law-abiding civilians were transformed into para-military secret agents, equipped with silent killing techniques and trained in unarmed combat. This fascinating, timely and engaging book is concerned with the ways in which the SOE veterans reconstruct their wartime experiences of recruitment, training, clandestine work and for some, their captivity, focusing specifically upon the significance of gender and their attempts to pass as French civilians. This examination of the agents of an officially-sponsored insurgent organisation makes a major contribution to British socio-cultural history, war studies and gender studies and will appeal to both the general reader, as well as to those in the academic community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex rolezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpieszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen spieszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, British. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, Female. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSecret servicezGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xUnderground movementszFrance. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aBritish organisation.  aFrench civilians.  aSecond World War.  aSpecial Operations Executive.  aclandestine warfare.  ademobilisation.  afemininity.  afilmic representation.  agender relations.  amasculinity.  awartime experiences.1 aPattinson, Juliette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616224340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526162243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co